of Representatives|U.S. Representative]] for {{ushr|PA|1|}}, serving since 1998, and the [[ranking member|ranking]] [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democrat]] on the [[United States House Committee on House Administration]] since 2007. He has been the Chairman to the Philadelphia Democratic Party since 1986, and is one of the few members of Congress who is also a county chairman (Philadelphia Democratic City Committee).\n\n==Early life, education, and pre-congressional career==\nBrady was born in [[Philadelphia]], the son of Enez (n\u00e9e Caterini) and Robert G. Brady, a [[police officer]]. His father was of [[Irish American|Irish]] descent, and his maternal grandparents were immigrants from [[Italian American|Italy]].<ref>[http://www.whorunsgov.com/Profiles/Robert_A._Brady Robert Brady profile]</ref> <ref>[http://freepages.genealogy.rootsweb.ancestry.com/%7Ebattle/reps/bradybob.htm Freepages profile at ancestry.com]</ref> He graduated from [[St. Thomas More High School]], but did not attend college, but went to work as a [[carpentry|carpenter]], becoming a part of the leadership of the union, and remains a member of several unions.<ref>[http://www.brady.house.gov/index.cfm?sectionid=117&sectiontree=2,117 Robert Brady House of Representatives website] </ref>\n\nHe was elected a precinct committeeman for the [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic Party]] in 1968. When wardleader and then-City Council President [[George X. Schwartz]] was convicted and imprisoned in the [[Abscam]] scandal, Brady was elected to succeed him as Democratic Leader of the 34th Ward, a position that he still holds today.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.seventy.org/Downloads/2009_Citizen's_Guide.pdf|title=2009 Citizen's Guide|accessdate=2009-12-21|last=[[Committee of Seventy]]|date=2009-12-21|format=PDF|work= 2009 Citizen's Guide|publisher=The Committee of Seventy, Philadelphia, PA 19103}}</ref> Since June 1986, Brady has been the Chairman of the Philadelphia Democratic Party. He served as a staff aide in the [[Philadelphia City Council]] and a staff aide in the [[Pennsylvania State Senate]]. Brady has been an instructor at the [[University of Pennsylvania]]. He was also a member of the [[Pennsylvania Turnpike Commission]] from 1991 until his election as a Congressman.\n\n==U.S. House of Representatives==\n===Elections===\n{{See also|United States House of Representatives elections in Pennsylvania, 2012#District 1}}\nWhen 17-year U.S. Congressman [[Tom Foglietta]] resigned from the [[United States House of Representatives|House of Representatives]] upon being named [[U.S. Ambassador]] to [[Italy]] by [[Bill Clinton]], Brady was unopposed in the primary and won the general election with 74% of the vote. Brady was sworn in on May 19, 1998. He has won re-election since, with at least 81% of the vote.\n\n===Tenure===\n;Abortion\nBrady is pro-choice and voted against President Bush's restrictions on funding to family planning groups in 2001. Over the years, he has supported minors\u2019 abortion rights, voting in 2005 for the right for those under 18 years of age to obtain abortions across state lines without parental consent.<ref name=\"ontheissues\">[http://www.ontheissues.org/PA/Robert_Brady_Abortion.htm], Robert Brady on Abortion. Retrieved November 23, 2010.</ref> He voted against the Stupak-Pitts Amendment, which prohibits health insurance companies from offering abortion coverage in a plan to any citizen. He opposed a proposal to prohibit federally funded abortion services.<ref name=\"thatsmycongress: an independent voice on campaigns and legislations\">[http://thatsmycongress.com/house/repBradyPA1111.html], Representative Robert Brady. Retrieved November  23, 2010.</ref> Over the past fifteen years, organizations such as the National Association for the Repeal of Abortion Laws (NARAL), the National Family Planning & Reproductive Health Association, and Planned Parenthood rated him 100%.<ref name=\"projectvotesmart\">[http://www.votesmart.org/issue_rating_category.php?can_id=2519], Interest Group Ratings. Retrieved November 23, 2010.</ref>\n\n;Budget and Spending\nBrady supports the growth of small businesses and voted in favor of the Small Business Lending Fund and Tax Law Amendment. The recent amendment, passed in September 2010, provides loans to small business through financial institutions.<ref name=\"projectvotesmart\">[http://www.votesmart.org/issue_keyvote_detail.php?cs_id=32155&can_id=2519], Key Vote: Small Business Lending Fund and Tax Law Amendments. Retrieved November 23, 2010.</ref> He, along with the House, passed the Small Business Jobs Bill in October 2010 to provide millions of small businesses with the tax relief and access to credit that they need to expand, grow, and hire workers.<ref name=\"projectvotesmart\">[http://www.votesmart.org/speech_detail.php?sc_id=615031&keyword=small+business&phrase=&contain=], Representative Robert Brady. Retrieved November 23, 2010.</ref> \n\n;Immigration\nBrady supports a liberal stance on immigration as well. He voted against the Secure Fence Act (2006), which authorized the construction of additional fencing along the U.S.-Mexico border, as well as the Immigration Law Enforcement Act of 2006.<ref name=\"projectvotesmart\">[http://www.votesmart.org/issue_keyvote_detail.php?cs_id=8235&can_id=2519], Key Vote: Secure Fence Act of 2006. Retrieved November 23, 2010.</ref> He does continue to support Homeland Security Appropriations for border protection, in addition to the U.S. Visitor and Immigrant Status Technology project.<ref name=\"projectvotesmart\">[http://www.votesmart.org/issue_keyvote_detail.php?cs_id=8512&can_id=2519], Key Vote: Department of Homeland Security Appropriations Act. Retrieved November 23, 2010.</ref> The program works towards improving the nation's capability to keep track of immigrants and control their entry and exit.<ref name=\"EPIC\">[http://epic.org/privacy/us-visit/], U.S. VISIT. Retrieved November 24, 2010.</ref> Groups such as the National Latino Congreso/William C. Vel\u00e1squez Institute, the American Immigration Lawyers Association, and the [[Federation for American Immigration Reform]] have rated Brady between 50% and 100% for his pro-immigration political stances.<ref name=\"projectvotesmart\"/>\n\n[[File:Robert Brady.jpg|thumb|Brady with President Clinton]]\n\n===Committee assignments===\n* '''[[United States House Committee on Armed Services|Committee on Armed Services]]'''\n** [[United States House Armed Services Subcommittee on Military Personnel|Subcommittee on Military Personnel]]\n* '''[[United States House Committee on House Administration|Committee on House Administration]]''' (Ranking Member)\n** [[United States House Administration Subcommittee on Elections|Subcommittee on Elections]] (Ranking Member)\n\n===Caucus memberships===\n* Congressional Arts Caucus\n\n==2007 Mayoral campaign==\n{{main|2007 Philadelphia Mayoral Election}}\nOn January 25, 2007 Brady announced that he would seek the Democratic Party nomination for mayor of Philadelphia. He was the second sitting U.S. Congressman after [[Chaka Fattah]] to announce his candidacy for mayor.<ref>{{cite news|last=Lucey|first=Catherine|title=Starting Today, he's in the race|publisher=Philadelphia Daily News|date=January 25, 2007|url=http://www.thenextmayor.com/vault/20070125Brady.html|accessdate=2007-04-13|archiveurl=http://web.archive.org/web/20070927215403/http://www.thenextmayor.com/vault/20070125Brady.html|archivedate=September 27, 2007}}</ref> On March 6, Brady failed to list his city pension on the financial-interests statement he filed with his nominating petitions. Within a week [[Milton Street]] filed a petition challenge to remove Brady from the ballot for failing to disclose his pension income. Another challenge was brought by a group of voters, and supported by mayoral candidates [[Tom Knox]] and Dwight Evans. On April 13, 2007, the [[Commonwealth Court of Pennsylvania|Pennsylvania Commonwealth Court]] ruled that Brady's failure to not list part of his income would not keep him off the primary ballot.<ref>{{cite news|title=Court Ruling Keeps Brady On Mayoral Primary Ballot|agency=Associated Press|date=April 13, 2007|url=http://cbs3.com/topstories/local_story_103165943.html|accessdate=2007-04-13|archiveurl=http://web.archive.org/web/20080209140220/http://cbs3.com/topstories/local_story_103165943.html|archivedate=February 9, 2008}}</ref> On May 15, 2007, Brady lost the Democratic mayoral primary to [[Michael Nutter]].\n\n==Power and influence==\n* The ''[[Philadelphia Inquirer]]'' described him as ''\"the longtime boss of the Democratic City Committee, one of the few old-fashioned big-city political machines left. Running against him could equal career suicide.\"''<ref>[http://articles.philly.com/2011-10-18/news/30292983_1_bob-brady-dropout-rate-campaign-event Brady profile, ''Phialdelphia Inquirer'']</ref>\n\n* In 2001, the political website [[PoliticsPA]] described him as a \"consummate 'backroom politician' (and we say that with respect!)\" and said that he might be the best county party chair in [[Pennsylvania]].<ref name=countychairs>{{cite web| title =PA's Best and Worst County Chairs| work = [[PoliticsPA]]| publisher =The Publius Group| year=2001|url=http://www.politicspa.com/FEATURES/Best&Worst.htm|archiveurl=http://web.archive.org/web/20030212173818/politicspa.com/FEATURES/Best&Worst.htm|archivedate=2003-02-12}}</ref> In 2003, the ''[[Pennsylvania Report]]'' said that Brady has \"managed effectively to balance his multiracial district and city Democrat party.\"<ref name=pareport2003>{{cite web|title=The PA Report \"Power 75\" List|work=[[Pennsylvania Report]]|publisher=Capital Growth, Inc.|date=January 31, 2003|url=http://www.pa-report.com/uploaded_pdf/PAReportPower75_.pdf|archiveurl=http://web.archive.org/web/20060920200116/www.pa-report.com/uploaded_pdf/PAReportPower75_.pdf|archivedate=2006-09-02|format=PDF}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|last=Roarty|first=Alex|author2=Sean Coit|title=Pennsylvania Influencers|newspaper=[[Politics Magazine]]|pages=44\u201349|date=January 2010|url=http://politicsmagazine.com/uploads/Image/Politics_PA_influencers_web.pdf|archiveurl=http://www.webcitation.org/5nNQI9Qgt|archivedate=2010-02-07}}</ref> \n\n* In 2009, the ''[[Pennsylvania Report]]'' noted that \"[w]hile he still would like to be Mayor, Brady's influence and power in Philadelphia remains strong.\"<ref name=pareport2009>{{cite web| title = PA Report 100| work=[[Pennsylvania Report]]|publisher=Capital Growth, Inc.|date=January 23, 2009|url=http://www.pa-report.com/uploaded_pdf/PA%20Report%20100%20-%20Jan%2023,%202009.pdf|archiveurl=http://www.webcitation.org/5j0zKOG5a|archivedate=2009-08-14|format=PDF}}</ref>\n\n* Pennsylvania State Senator [[Anthony H. Williams|Anthony Williams]] said he is \"probably one of the most politically astute politicians in the last 20 years, and that's rarefied air.\" [[J. Whyatt Mondesire]], head of the Philadelphia chapter of the [[NAACP]], said no one can match \"Brady's relationships with politicians across the Democratic landscape.\"<ref>[http://articles.philly.com/2011-10-18/news/30292983_1_bob-brady-dropout-rate-campaign-event/2 Anthony Williams quote re Brady]</ref>\n\n== Electoral History ==\n*'''2014 Election to the US House'''<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.electionreturns.state.pa.us/Default.aspx?EID=41&ESTID=2&CID=0&OID=11&CDID=0&PID=0&DISTID=0&IsSpecial=0&PageRefID=1|title=2014 General Election Unofficial Returns|date=November 4, 2014|accessdate=November 9, 2014}}</ref> \n**Bob Brady (D) (inc.), 83%\n**Megan Ann Rath (R), 17%\n*'''2012 Election to the US House'''<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.electionreturns.state.pa.us/ElectionsInformation.aspx?FunctionID=13&ElectionID=53&OfficeID=11|title=2012 General Election Official Returns|date=November 6, 2012|accessdate=December 19, 2012}}</ref> \n**Bob Brady (D) (inc.), 85%\n**John Featherman (R), 15.1%\n* '''2010 Election to the US House'''<ref name=\"APelections\" />\n** Bob Brady (D) (inc.), unopposed\n* '''2008 Election to US House'''<ref name=\"APelections\" />\n** Bob Brady (D) (inc.), 91%\n** Mike Muhammad (R), 9%\n* '''2006 Election to the US House'''<ref name=\"APelections\" />\n** Bob Brady (D) (inc.), unopposed\n* '''2004 Election to the US House'''<ref name=\"APelections\" />\n** Bob Brady (D) (inc.), 86%\n** Deborah Williams (R), 13%\n* '''2002 Election to the US House'''<ref name=\"APelections\" />\n** Bob Brady (D) (inc.), 86%\n** Marie Delaney (R), 12%\n* '''2000 Election to US House'''<ref name=\"APelections\" />\n** Bob Brady (D) (inc.), 88%\n** Steve Kush (R), 12%\n* '''1998 Election to US House'''<ref name=\"APelections\" />\n** Bob Brady (D) (inc.), 81%\n** William Harrison (R), 17%\n* '''1998 Special Election to US House'''<ref name=\"APelections\">{{cite news\n|url = http://elections.suntimes.com/dynamic/external/pre-election/profilesdistricts/PA01.html?SITE=ILCHSELN&SECTION=POLITICS\n|title = Pennsylvania House District 1\n|accessdate = 2008-04-07\n|agency = Associated Press\n|authorlink = The Associated Press\n|publisher = Chicago Sun-Times\n|archiveurl = \n|archivedate = \n}}</ref>\n** Bob Brady (D), 74%\n** William Harrison (R), 13%\n** Juanita Norwood (Reform), 11%\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{commonscat-inline}}\n* [http://brady.house.gov/ Congressman Robert A. Brady] official U.S. House site\n* [http://www.bobbrady.us/ Robert A. Brady for Congress] \n*{{Dmoz|Regional/North_America/United_States/Pennsylvania/Government/Federal/US_House_of_Representatives/Robert_A._Brady_%5BD-1%5D|Robert Brady}}\n*{{CongLinks | congbio=b001227 | ballot = Robert_A._Brady | nndb = 397/000032301 | votesmart = 2519 | govtrack = 400047 | opencong = 400047 | rollcall = 408 | politifact = | fec = H8PA01153 | opensecrets = N00001619 | assets = robert-brady | legistorm = 146/Rep_Robert_A_Brady.html | followthemoney = | ontheissues = PA/Robert_Brady.htm | congress = robert-brady/1469